         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Kew Dec 8th/61. ¶ Dr Dr Mueller ¶  ¶ I have little to say but that we are all well &amp; busy. Thanks for your last with the accompanying enclosure. ¶  What a kind fellow Harvey is. I am sure you have act...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">61.12.08</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M3, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Kew Dec 8th/61.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dr Dr Mueller</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have little to say but that we are all well &amp; busy. Thanks for your last with the accompanying enclosure.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to J. Hooker, 24 September 1861.</p>
               </note> What a kind fellow Harvey is. I am sure you have acted both liberally &amp; wisely. — Bentham has already begun with the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Dilleniaceae">Dilleniaceae</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>. having to revise that order for Gen. Plant.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> he took the opportunity of doing the Australian species — he found a good many in Brit: Mus. that were unknown elsewhere. Sonder is sending over all Plant Preiss<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Plants collected by Ludwig Preiss in WA, 1838–42.</p>
               </note> but they have not arrived yet. I very much hope that you will get on with Victoria Flora;<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B62.02.01.</p>
               </note> it is a capital work, &amp; will cost you more labor than you perhaps anticipate to complete it.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We have just gone to press with the 1st part of Genera Plantarum but it will be 4 months before it is out. The Sapind.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <name key="Sapindaceae">Sapindaceae</name>.</p>
               </note> Terebinth<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <name key="Terebinthaceae">Terebinthaceae</name>, a Jussieu group that Bentham and Hooker distributed between a number of different orders.</p>
               </note> &amp; all these orders have cost us immense labor. as it is we have been 3 years at DC vol I!<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A. P. de Candolle (1823-73). Vol 1 of this work includes orders from I Ranunculaceae to LIV Coriarieae, while the first volume of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Genera plantarum </seg>covers orders up to LVI Connaraceae.</p>
               </note> We hope however to get on faster after this &amp; this work will facilitate local Floras very much indeed.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Welwitch has sent the Tumboa to be described by me in Linn. Trans. as <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Welwitschia">Welwitschia</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>,<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Hooker (1863).</p>
               </note> it is certainly the most marvellous plant discovered since Botany was systematized — more curious certainly though less striking in some points than <name key="Rafflesia">Rafflesia</name> — it is certainly <name key="Gnetaceae">Gnetaceae</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Baines has sent us a sketch of the same thing from Dammara land<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Damaraland in southern Africa, part of modern Namibia.</p>
               </note> together with very imperfect specimens.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We continue to receive very remarkable collections from our West African collector Mann,<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Gustav Mann.</p>
               </note> who is now at St Thomas<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>São Tomé.</p>
               </note> &amp; going to Cameroons mountains.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever most ty yrs</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Jos D Hooker</p>
